    <section id="tech" class="home-part">  
      <div class="container">
<img src="image/questionbg.jpg">
        <div class="section-heading-wrapper"><h3>Technology and Computers</h3></div>
        <h4> I am very interested in Cryptology and Security. I have a secondary research interest in Artificial Intelligence, especially in the fields of Machine Learning and Pattern Recognition. I have always been interested in interdisciplinary pursuits. I have been told that I have some aggressively progressive ideas. For example, there are some mathematical proofs that are absolutely beautiful, simple and elegant. But there are others which can be automated. Whenever I see a logical analysis, or a proof, I try and ask: Could this be generalized? Can this be automated? Would it be too hard to teach a computer how to do it? Because, hey, if you can, then you just saved a lot of brain-time (and paper: go green). You can just enter a few parameters here and there and let a computer do it for you, while you can go catch that movie that everyone else has already seen. Because whether you like it or not, computers <b> are </b> better than human beings at computation - <i> if </i> you teach them how to do it in the first place. </h4>
       
      </div>
    </section> <!-- SKILLS END -->
    
    

    <section id="project" class="home-part">
      <div class="container">
        <div class="section-heading-wrapper"><h3 id="experience-position">Projects</h3></div>
        <div class="clearfix"></div>

        <div class="row">

          <div class="animation-wrapper" data-uk-scrollspy="{cls:&#39;uk-animation-slide-bottom&#39;, delay: 500, repeat: true}">
          <div class="col-md-4">
            <div class="company">
              <img src="image/password9.png" alt="">
            </div> <!-- COMPANY END -->

            <div class="recruit">
              <h4>Hash Function Cryptanalysis</h4>
              <h5></h5>
            </div><!-- RECRUIT END -->
          </div> <!-- col-md-4 end -->

          <div class="col-md-8">
            <h4>Hashes are like digital fingerprints.</h4>

            <p> <ul>It is supposed to be unique, but it isn't; although finding a duplicate should be extremely tough. If there's a mix-up, it can lead to very drastic consequences - including theft, credit card frauds or even <a href="http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Flame_(malware)">international cyber-espionage.</a> My work involves analyzing the security of these algorithms.
                </ul>
            </p>

            
          </div> <!-- col-md-8 end -->

          <div class="x-devider"></div> <!-- experience item deivder -->
          </div> <!-- ANIMATION WRAPPER END-->
          
          <div class="animation-wrapper" data-uk-scrollspy="{cls:&#39;uk-animation-slide-bottom&#39;, delay: 800, repeat: true}">
          <div class="col-md-4">
            <div class="company">
              <img src="image/magnifying2.png" alt="">
            </div> <!-- company end -->

            <div class="recruit">
              <h4>Crime HotSpots</h4>
              <h5></h5>
            </div><!-- RECRUIT END -->
          </div> <!-- col-md-4 end -->

          <div class="col-md-8">
            <h4>Sherlock++</h4>

            <p><ul>Wouldn't it be great if we could use the available crime statistics to find and detect patterns of crimes, a la Sherlock Holmes, and try to prevent future crimes? Wouldn't it be even better if we could teach computers to do that automatically?
              </ul> </p>

           
          </div> <!-- col-md-8 end -->
<div class="x-devider"></div> <!-- experience item deivder -->
          </div> <!-- ANIMATION WRAPPER END-->
<div class="animation-wrapper" data-uk-scrollspy="{cls:&#39;uk-animation-slide-bottom&#39;, delay: 800, repeat: true}">
          <div class="col-md-4">
            <div class="company">
              <img src="image/small28.png" alt="">
            </div> <!-- company end -->

            <div class="recruit">
              <h4>Post-Quantum Cryptosystems</h4>
              <h5></h5>
            </div><!-- RECRUIT END -->
          </div> <!-- col-md-4 end -->

          <div class="col-md-8">
            <h4>To Byte or Not To Byte: The Schrodinger Cat's Question</h4>

            <p><ul>The systems that protect us from the bad guys on the internet today are reliant on the classical hardness of some mathematical problems - like integer factorization. (If you think integer factorization is easy, try factoring 1278413094240119485184501495145O8927359). (If you are trying that on online servers, don't. I slipped an O in between in place of a 0.) But quantum computers (these babies are born rockstars) can defeat some of them. To stay ahead, we need to find out more about systems that are quantum attack-proof.
              </ul> </p> 

           
          </div> <!-- col-md-8 end -->
<div class="x-devider"></div> <!-- experience item deivder -->
          </div> <!-- ANIMATION WRAPPER END-->

<div class="animation-wrapper" data-uk-scrollspy="{cls:&#39;uk-animation-slide-bottom&#39;, delay: 800, repeat: true}">
          <div class="col-md-4">
            <div class="company">
              <img src="image/protection6.png" alt="">
            </div> <!-- company end -->

            <div class="recruit">
              <h4>Coding Theory</h4>
              <h5></h5>
            </div><!-- RECRUIT END -->
          </div> <!-- col-md-4 end -->

          <div class="col-md-8">
            <h4>Coding Theory is NOT Cryptography</h4>

            <p><ul>But crypto uses coding theory in some places. In fact, some cryptosystems rely heavily on coding theory. A prominent example would be the McEliece system. However, this one is a double-edged sword - and we are trying to find out how to wield it cleanly.
              </ul> </p>

           
          </div> <!-- col-md-8 end -->
<div class="x-devider"></div> <!-- experience item deivder -->
          </div> <!-- ANIMATION WRAPPER END-->

